he Jewish community, women who intermarried later in the century were more likely to raise their children with strong ties to Judaism than women who intermarried earlier in the century. Bringing perennially controversial questions of Jewish identity, continuity, and survival to the forefront of the discussion, Still Jewish addresses topics of great resonance in the modern Jewish community and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIntermarriagezUnited States. 0aJewish women. 0aJewsxCultural assimilation. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aJewish.  aKeren.  aMcGinity.  aacross.  acentury.  aclosely.  acontext.  adecisions.  adescribes.  aexamining.  agender.  ahistorical.  aintermarriage.  aintermarried.  aintersection.  alives.  aplacing.  atheir.  atwentieth.  awhile.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475730740uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814757307.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759615423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814759615/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK